		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Masquerade (book)</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:156px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Masquerade-book.jpg" class="image" title="Masquerade, 1979"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/46/Masquerade-book.jpg" width="154" height="200" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Masquerade-book.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Masquerade, 1979</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><i><b>Masquerade</b></i> is a children’s book, written and painted by <a href="/wiki/Kit_Williams" title="Kit Williams">Kit Williams</a>, which sparked a worldwide treasure hunt by concealing clues to the location of a jewelled golden <a href="/wiki/Hare" title="Hare">hare</a>, created and hidden somewhere in <a href="/wiki/Great_Britain" title="Great Britain">Britain</a> by Williams. It became the inspiration for a genre of books known today as <a href="/wiki/Armchair_treasure_hunt" title="Armchair treasure hunt" class="mw-redirect">armchair treasure hunts</a>.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
